ce:section.ce:para:
The schematic of the preparation process of different molecular weight polymer passivated GQDs is shown in Fig. 1
                     . The surface of GQDs which have been passivated by polymer with larger molecular weight has longer chains functional group, which brings enhanced luminescence of GQDs. To explore the optical properties of passivated GQDs, PL, PLE and UV–vis absorption spectra were studied (Fig. 2
                     ). In Fig. 2a, the PL spectra of different molecular weight PEG passivated GQDs at 360 nm excitation wavelength is showed. It is obvious that as the molecular weight of PEG increases from 1000 to 6000, the PL intensity of corresponding GQDs becomes stronger. While the shape of curves remains consistent, that is, the position of the fluorescence peak remains basically unchanged. The strongest peak in the PL spectrum is at 425 nm, which shows corresponding Stokes shift of 65 nm. Fig. 2b presents the corresponding PL excitation (PLE) spectrum with fixed detected emission wavelength of 425 nm. Obviously, the shape of the emission spectrum is also consistent. It can be found GQDs can be induced to generate the strongest emission peak of 425 nm by the excitation wavelength at ca. 370 nm, but not at 360 nm. The UV–visible absorption spectrum is shown in Fig. 2c. Similarly, the absorption peaks of the three GQDs are consistent, where the strongest absorption peaks are located at ca.305 nm, and the absorption edges are same. According to the inset image in Fig. 2c, it can be observed that the GQDs solution emits blue luminescence under 365 nm UV light. And with the increase of molecular weight of PEG, the blue luminescence becomes more and more obvious.
